# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cmos-technology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 1948, John Bardeen and Walter Brattain, the original inventors of transistor technology, patented an insulated-gate transistor (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Bardeen's concept forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The CMOS process was presented by Fairchild Semiconductor's Frank Wanlass and Chih-Tang Sah at the International Solid-State Circuits Conference in 1963.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Wanlass later filed US patent 3,356,858 for CMOS circuitry and it was granted in 1967.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RCA commercialized the technology with the trademark "COS-MOS" in the late 1960s, forcing other manufacturers to find another name, leading to "CMOS" becoming the standard name for the technology by the early 1970s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Two important characteristics of CMOS devices are high noise immunity and low static power consumption.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Since one transistor of the MOSFET pair is always off, the series combination draws significant power only momentarily during switching between on and off states.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Consequently, CMOS devices do not produce as much waste heat as other forms of logic, like NMOS logic or transistor–transistor logic (TTL), which normally have some standing current even when not changing state.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] These characteristics allow CMOS to integrate a high density of logic functions on a chip.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] It was primarily for this reason that CMOS became the most widely used technology to be implemented in VLSI chips.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The phrase "metal–oxide–semiconductor" is a reference to the physical structure of MOS field-effect transistors, having a metal gate electrode placed on top of an oxide insulator, which in turn is on top of a semiconductor material.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Aluminium was once used but now the material is polysilicon.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Other metal gates have made a comeback with the advent of high-κ dielectric materials in the CMOS process, as announced by IBM and Intel for the 45 nanometer node and smaller sizes.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS technology is also used for analog circuits such as image sensors (CMOS sensors), data converters, RF circuits (RF CMOS), and highly integrated transceivers for many types of communication.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The principle of complementary symmetry was first introduced by George Sziklai in 1953 who then discussed several complementary bipolar circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Paul Weimer, also at RCA, invented in 1962 thin-film transistor (TFT) complementary circuits, a close relative of CMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] He invented complementary flip-flop and inverter circuits, but did no work in a more complex complementary logic.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] He was the first person able to put p-channel and n-channel TFTs in a circuit on the same substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Marcus published a variety of complex logic functions implemented as integrated circuits using JFETs, including complementary memory circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Frank Wanlass was familiar with work done by Weimer at RCA.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 1955, Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derick accidentally grew a layer of silicon dioxide over the silicon wafer, for which they observed surface passivation effects.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] By 1957, Frosch and Derick, using masking and predeposition, were able to manufacture silicon transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] They showed that silicon dioxide protected silicon wafers from dopants diffusing into the wafer, and insulated the wafer from damage due to heat during the process.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Spitzer studied the mechanism of thermally grown oxides and fabricated a high quality Si/SiO2 stack in 1960.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Following this research, Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng proposed a silicon MOS transistor in 1959 and successfully demonstrated a working MOS device with their Bell Labs team in 1960.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] There were originally two types of MOSFET logic, PMOS (p-type MOS) and NMOS (n-type MOS).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 1948, Bardeen and Brattain patented the progenitor of MOSFET, an insulated-gate FET (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Bardeen's patent, and the concept of an inversion layer, forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] A new type of MOSFET logic combining both the PMOS and NMOS processes was developed, called complementary MOS (CMOS), by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In February 1963, they published the invention in a research paper.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In both the research paper and the patent filed by Wanlass, the fabrication of CMOS devices was outlined, on the basis of thermal oxidation of a silicon substrate to yield a layer of silicon dioxide located between the drain contact and the source contact.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS was commercialised by RCA in the late 1960s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RCA adopted CMOS for the design of integrated circuits (ICs), developing CMOS circuits for an Air Force computer in 1965 and then a 288-bit CMOS SRAM memory chip in 1968.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RCA also used CMOS for its 4000-series integrated circuits in 1968, starting with a 20 μm semiconductor manufacturing process before gradually scaling to a 10 μm process over the next several years.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS technology was initially overlooked by the American semiconductor industry in favour of NMOS, which was more powerful at the time.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] However, CMOS was quickly adopted and further advanced by Japanese semiconductor manufacturers due to its low power consumption, leading to the rise of the Japanese semiconductor industry.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Toshiba developed C2MOS (*clocked CMOS*), a circuit technology with lower power consumption and faster operating speed than ordinary CMOS, in 1969.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Toshiba used its C2MOS technology to develop a large-scale integration (LSI) chip for Sharp's Elsi Mini LED pocket calculator, developed in 1971 and released in 1972.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Suwa Seikosha (now Seiko Epson) began developing a CMOS IC chip for a Seiko quartz watch in 1969, and began mass-production with the launch of the Seiko Analog Quartz 38SQW watch in 1971.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The first mass-produced CMOS consumer electronic product was the Hamilton Pulsar "Wrist Computer" digital watch, released in 1970.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Due to low power consumption, CMOS logic has been widely used for calculators and watches since the 1970s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The earliest microprocessors in the early 1970s were PMOS processors, which initially dominated the early microprocessor industry.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] By the late 1970s, NMOS microprocessors had overtaken PMOS processors.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS microprocessors were introduced in 1975, with the Intersil 6100, and RCA CDP 1801.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] However, CMOS processors did not become dominant until the 1980s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS was initially slower than NMOS logic, thus NMOS was more widely used for computers in the 1970s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The Intel 5101 (1 kb SRAM) CMOS memory chip (1974) had an access time of 800 ns, whereas the fastest NMOS chip at the time, the Intel 2147 (4 kb SRAM) HMOS memory chip (1976), had an access time of 55/70 ns.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 1978, a Hitachi research team led by Toshiaki Masuhara introduced the twin-well Hi-CMOS process, with its HM6147 (4 kb SRAM) memory chip, manufactured with a 3 μm process.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The Hitachi HM6147 chip was able to match the performance (55/70 ns access) of the Intel 2147 HMOS chip, while the HM6147 also consumed significantly less power (15 mA) than the 2147 (110 mA).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] With comparable performance and much less power consumption, the twin-well CMOS process eventually overtook NMOS as the most common semiconductor manufacturing process for computers in the 1980s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In the 1980s, CMOS microprocessors overtook NMOS microprocessors.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] NASA's Galileo spacecraft, sent to orbit Jupiter in 1989, used the RCA 1802 CMOS microprocessor due to low power consumption.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Intel introduced a 1.5 μm process for CMOS semiconductor device fabrication in 1983.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In the mid-1980s, Bijan Davari of IBM developed high-performance, low-voltage, deep sub-micron CMOS technology, which enabled the development of faster computers as well as portable computers and battery-powered handheld electronics.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 1988, Davari led an IBM team that demonstrated a high-performance 250 nanometer CMOS process.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Fujitsu commercialized a 700 nm CMOS process in 1987, and then Hitachi, Mitsubishi Electric, NEC and Toshiba commercialized 500 nm CMOS in 1989.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 1993, Sony commercialized a 350 nm CMOS process, while Hitachi and NEC commercialized 250 nm CMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Hitachi introduced a 160 nm CMOS process in 1995, then Mitsubishi introduced 150 nm CMOS in 1996, and then Samsung Electronics introduced 140 nm in 1999.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In 2000, Gurtej Singh Sandhu and Trung T.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Doan at Micron Technology invented atomic layer deposition high-κ dielectric films, leading to the development of a cost-effective 90 nm CMOS process.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Toshiba and Sony developed a 65 nm CMOS process in 2002, and then TSMC initiated the development of 45 nm CMOS logic in 2004.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The development of pitch double patterning by Gurtej Singh Sandhu at Micron Technology led to the development of 30 nm class CMOS in the 2000s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS is used in most modern LSI and VLSI devices.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] As of 2010, CPUs with the best performance per watt each year have been CMOS static logic since 1976.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] As of 2019, planar CMOS technology is still the most common form of semiconductor device fabrication, but is gradually being replaced by non-planar FinFET technology, which is capable of manufacturing semiconductor nodes smaller than 20 nm.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] "CMOS" refers to both a particular style of digital circuitry design and the family of processes used to implement that circuitry on integrated circuits (chips).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS circuitry dissipates less power than logic families with resistive loads.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Since this advantage has increased and grown more important, CMOS processes and variants have come to dominate, thus the vast majority of modern integrated circuit manufacturing is on CMOS processes.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS logic consumes around one seventh the power of NMOS logic, and about 10 million times less power than bipolar transistor–transistor logic (TTL).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS circuits use a combination of p-type and n-type metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFETs) to implement logic gates and other digital circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Although CMOS logic can be implemented with discrete devices for demonstrations, commercial CMOS products are integrated circuits composed of up to billions of transistors of both types, on a rectangular piece of silicon of often between 10 and 400 mm2.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS always uses all enhancement-mode MOSFETs (in other words, a zero gate-to-source voltage turns the transistor off).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS circuits are constructed in such a way that all p-type metal–oxide–semiconductor (PMOS) transistors must have either an input from the voltage source or from another PMOS transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Similarly, all NMOS transistors must have either an input from ground or from another NMOS transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The composition of a PMOS transistor creates low resistance between its source and drain contacts when a low gate voltage is applied and high resistance when a high gate voltage is applied.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] On the other hand, the composition of an NMOS transistor creates high resistance between source and drain when a low gate voltage is applied and low resistance when a high gate voltage is applied.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS accomplishes current reduction by complementing every nMOSFET with a pMOSFET and connecting both gates and both drains together.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] A high voltage on the gates will cause the nMOSFET to conduct and the pMOSFET not to conduct, while a low voltage on the gates causes the reverse.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This arrangement greatly reduces power consumption and heat generation.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] However, during the switching time, both pMOS and nMOS MOSFETs conduct briefly as the gate voltage transitions from one state to another.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This induces a brief spike in power consumption and becomes a serious issue at high frequencies.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The adjacent image shows what happens when an input is connected to both a PMOS transistor (top of diagram) and an NMOS transistor (bottom of diagram).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Vdd is some positive voltage connected to a power supply and Vss is ground.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] When the voltage of A is low (i.e. close to Vss), the NMOS transistor's channel is in a high resistance state, disconnecting Vss from Q.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The PMOS transistor's channel is in a low resistance state, connecting Vdd to Q.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] On the other hand, when the voltage of A is high (i.e. close to Vdd), the PMOS transistor is in a high resistance state, disconnecting Vdd from Q.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The NMOS transistor is in a low resistance state, connecting Vss to Q.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In short, the outputs of the PMOS and NMOS transistors are complementary such that when the input is low, the output is high, and when the input is high, the output is low.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] No matter what the input is, the output is never left floating (charge is never stored due to wire capacitance and lack of electrical drain/ground).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Because of this behavior of input and output, the CMOS circuit's output is the inverse of the input.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The transistors' resistances are never exactly equal to zero or infinity, so Q will never exactly equal Vss or Vdd, but Q will always be closer to Vss than A was to Vdd (or vice versa if A were close to Vss).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Without this amplification, there would be a very low limit to the number of logic gates that could be chained together in series, and CMOS logic with billions of transistors would be impossible.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The power supply pins for CMOS are called *VDD* and *VSS*, or *VCC* and *ground (GND)* depending on the manufacturer.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] *VDD* and *VSS* are carryovers from conventional MOS circuits and stand for the *drain* and *source* supplies.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] These do not apply directly to CMOS, since both supplies are really source supplies.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] *VCC* and *ground* are carryovers from TTL logic and that nomenclature has been retained with the introduction of the 54C/74C line of CMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] An important characteristic of a CMOS circuit is the duality that exists between its PMOS transistors and NMOS transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] A CMOS circuit is created to allow a path always to exist from the output to either the power source or ground.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] To accomplish this, the set of all paths to the voltage source must be the complement of the set of all paths to ground.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This can be easily accomplished by defining one in terms of the NOT of the other.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Due to the logic based on De Morgan's laws, the PMOS transistors in parallel have corresponding NMOS transistors in series while the PMOS transistors in series have corresponding NMOS transistors in parallel.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] More complex logic functions such as those involving AND and OR gates require manipulating the paths between gates to represent the logic.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] When a path consists of two transistors in series, both transistors must have low resistance to the corresponding supply voltage, modelling an AND.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] When a path consists of two transistors in parallel, either one or both of the transistors must have low resistance to connect the supply voltage to the output, modelling an OR.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Shown on the right is a circuit diagram of a NAND gate in CMOS logic.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] If both of the A and B inputs are high, then both the NMOS transistors (bottom half of the diagram) will conduct, neither of the PMOS transistors (top half) will conduct, and a conductive path will be established between the output and *V*ss (ground), bringing the output low.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] If both of the A and B inputs are low, then neither of the NMOS transistors will conduct, while both of the PMOS transistors will conduct, establishing a conductive path between the output and *V*dd (voltage source), bringing the output high.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] If either of the A or B inputs is low, one of the NMOS transistors will not conduct, one of the PMOS transistors will, and a conductive path will be established between the output and *V*dd (voltage source), bringing the output high.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] As the only configuration of the two inputs that results in a low output is when both are high, this circuit implements a NAND (NOT AND) logic gate.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] An advantage of CMOS over NMOS logic is that both low-to-high and high-to-low output transitions are fast since the (PMOS) pull-up transistors have low resistance when switched on, unlike the load resistors in NMOS logic.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In addition, the output signal swings the full voltage between the low and high rails.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This strong, more nearly symmetric response also makes CMOS more resistant to noise.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] See Logical effort for a method of calculating delay in a CMOS circuit.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This example shows a NAND logic device drawn as a physical representation as it would be manufactured.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The physical layout perspective is a "bird's eye view" of a stack of layers.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The circuit is constructed on a p-type substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The polysilicon, diffusion, and n-well are referred to as "base layers" and are actually inserted into trenches of the p-type substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] (See steps 1 to 6 in the process diagram below right) The contacts penetrate an insulating layer between the base layers and the first layer of metal (metal1) making a connection.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The inputs to the NAND (illustrated in green color) are in polysilicon.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The transistors (devices) are formed by the intersection of the polysilicon and diffusion; N diffusion for the N device & P diffusion for the P device (illustrated in salmon and yellow coloring respectively).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The output ("out") is connected together in metal (illustrated in cyan coloring).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Connections between metal and polysilicon or diffusion are made through contacts (illustrated as black squares).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The physical layout example matches the NAND logic circuit given in the previous example.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The N device is manufactured on a p-type substrate while the P device is manufactured in an n-type well (n-well).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] A p-type substrate "tap" is connected to VSS and an n-type n-well tap is connected to VDD to prevent latchup.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS logic dissipates less power than NMOS logic circuits because CMOS dissipates power only when switching ("dynamic power").
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] On a typical ASIC in a modern 90 nanometer process, switching the output might take 120 picoseconds, and happens once every ten nanoseconds.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] NMOS logic dissipates power whenever the transistor is on, because there is a current path from Vdd to Vss through the load resistor and the n-type network.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Static CMOS gates are very power efficient because they dissipate nearly zero power when idle.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Earlier, the power consumption of CMOS devices was not the major concern while designing chips.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Factors like speed and area dominated the design parameters.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] As the CMOS technology moved below sub-micron levels the power consumption per unit area of the chip has risen tremendously.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Both NMOS and PMOS transistors have a gate–source threshold voltage (Vth), below which the current (called *sub threshold* current) through the device will drop exponentially.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Historically, CMOS circuits operated at supply voltages much larger than their threshold voltages (Vdd might have been 5 V, and Vth for both NMOS and PMOS might have been 700 mV).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] A special type of the transistor used in some CMOS circuits is the native transistor, with near zero threshold voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] SiO2 is a good insulator, but at very small thickness levels electrons can tunnel across the very thin insulation; the probability drops off exponentially with oxide thickness.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Tunnelling current becomes very important for transistors below 130 nm technology with gate oxides of 20 Å or thinner.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Small reverse leakage currents are formed due to formation of reverse bias between diffusion regions and wells (for e.g., p-type diffusion vs. n-well), wells and substrate (for e.g., n-well vs. p-substrate).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In modern process diode leakage is very small compared to sub threshold and tunnelling currents, so these may be neglected during power calculations.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] If the ratios do not match, then there might be different currents of PMOS and NMOS; this may lead to imbalance and thus improper current causes the CMOS to heat up and dissipate power unnecessarily.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Furthermore, recent studies have shown that leakage power reduces due to aging effects as a trade-off for devices to become slower.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] To speed up designs, manufacturers have switched to constructions that have lower voltage thresholds but because of this a modern NMOS transistor with a Vth of 200 mV has a significant subthreshold leakage current.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Designs (e.g. desktop processors) which include vast numbers of circuits which are not actively switching still consume power because of this leakage current.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Leakage power is a significant portion of the total power consumed by such designs.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Multi-threshold CMOS (MTCMOS), now available from foundries, is one approach to managing leakage power.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] With MTCMOS, high Vth transistors are used when switching speed is not critical, while low Vth transistors are used in speed sensitive paths.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Further technology advances that use even thinner gate dielectrics have an additional leakage component because of current tunnelling through the extremely thin gate dielectric.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Using high-κ dielectrics instead of silicon dioxide that is the conventional gate dielectric allows similar device performance, but with a thicker gate insulator, thus avoiding this current.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Leakage power reduction using new material and system designs is critical to sustaining scaling of CMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS circuits dissipate power by charging the various load capacitances (mostly gate and wire capacitance, but also drain and some source capacitances) whenever they are switched.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] In one complete cycle of CMOS logic, current flows from VDD to the load capacitance to charge it and then flows from the charged load capacitance (CL) to ground during discharge.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Therefore, in one complete charge/discharge cycle, a total of Q=CLVDD is thus transferred from VDD to ground.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Multiply by the switching frequency on the load capacitances to get the current used, and multiply by the average voltage again to get the characteristic switching power dissipated by a CMOS device: $P=0.5CV^{2}f$ .
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Since most gates do not operate/switch at every clock cycle, they are often accompanied by a factor $\alpha$ , called the activity factor.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Now, the dynamic power dissipation may be re-written as $P=\alpha CV^{2}f$ .
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] A clock in a system has an activity factor α=1, since it rises and falls every cycle.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Most data has an activity factor of 0.1.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] If correct load capacitance is estimated on a node together with its activity factor, the dynamic power dissipation at that node can be calculated effectively.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Short-circuit power dissipation increases with the rise and fall time of the transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This form of power consumption became significant in the 1990s as wires on chip became narrower and the long wires became more resistive.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS gates at the end of those resistive wires see slow input transitions.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Careful design which avoids weakly driven long skinny wires reduces this effect, but crowbar power can be a substantial part of dynamic CMOS power.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Parasitic transistors that are inherent in the CMOS structure may be turned on by input signals outside the normal operating range, e.g. electrostatic discharges or line reflections.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The resulting latch-up may damage or destroy the CMOS device.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Clamp diodes are included in CMOS circuits to deal with these signals.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Manufacturers' data sheets specify the maximum permitted current that may flow through the diodes.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Besides digital applications, CMOS technology is also used in analog applications.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] For example, there are CMOS operational amplifier ICs available in the market.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Transmission gates may be used as analog multiplexers instead of signal relays.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] CMOS technology is also widely used for RF circuits all the way to microwave frequencies, in mixed-signal (analog+digital) applications.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RF CMOS refers to RF circuits (radio frequency circuits) which are based on mixed-signal CMOS integrated circuit technology.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] They are widely used in wireless telecommunication technology.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RF CMOS was developed by Asad Abidi while working at UCLA in the late 1980s.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This changed the way in which RF circuits were designed, leading to the replacement of discrete bipolar transistors with CMOS integrated circuits in radio transceivers.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] It enabled sophisticated, low-cost and portable end-user terminals, and gave rise to small, low-cost, low-power and portable units for a wide range of wireless communication systems.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] This enabled "anytime, anywhere" communication and helped bring about the wireless revolution, leading to the rapid growth of the wireless industry.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The baseband processors and radio transceivers in all modern wireless networking devices and mobile phones are mass-produced using RF CMOS devices.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Examples of commercial RF CMOS chips include Intel's DECT cordless phone, and 802.11 (Wi-Fi) chips created by Atheros and other companies.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Commercial RF CMOS products are also used for Bluetooth and wireless LAN (WLAN) networks.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RF CMOS is also used in the radio transceivers for wireless standards such as GSM, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth, transceivers for mobile networks such as 3G, and remote units in wireless sensor networks (WSN).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] RF CMOS technology is crucial to modern wireless communications, including wireless networks and mobile communication devices.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] One of the companies that commercialized RF CMOS technology was Infineon.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Its bulk CMOS RF switches sell over 1 billion units annually, reaching a cumulative 5 billion units, as of 2018.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Conventional CMOS devices work over a range of −55 °C to +125 °C.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] There were theoretical indications as early as August 2008 that silicon CMOS will work down to −233 °C (40 K).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Functioning temperatures near 40 K have since been achieved using overclocked AMD Phenom II processors with a combination of liquid nitrogen and liquid helium cooling.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Silicon carbide CMOS devices have been tested for a year at 500 °C.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] Ultra small (L = 20 nm, W = 20 nm) MOSFETs achieve the single-electron limit when operated at cryogenic temperature over a range of −269 °C (4 K) to about −258 °C (15 K).
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The transistor displays Coulomb blockade due to progressive charging of electrons one by one.
[src:cmos-technology/cmos] The number of electrons confined in the channel is driven by the gate voltage, starting from an occupation of zero electrons, and it can be set to one or many.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] These devices have been given the generic name "FinFETs" because the source/drain region forms fins on the silicon surface.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The FinFET devices exhibit significantly faster switching times and higher current density than planar CMOS (complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor) technology, resulting in enhanced performance and power efficiency.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] FinFET is a type of non-planar transistor, or "3D" transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] It is the basis for modern nanoelectronic semiconductor device fabrication.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Microchips utilizing FinFET gates first became commercialized in the first half of the 2010s, and became the dominant gate design at 14 nm, 10 nm and 7 nm process nodes.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] It is common for a single FinFET transistor to contain several fins, arranged side by side and all covered by the same gate, that act electrically as one.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The number of fins can be varied to adjust drive strength and performance, with drive strength increasing with a higher number of fins.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The concept of a double-gate thin-film transistor (TFT) was proposed by H.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] A double-gate MOSFET was later proposed by Toshihiro Sekigawa of the Electrotechnical Laboratory (ETL) in a 1980 patent describing the planar XMOS transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Sekigawa fabricated the XMOS transistor with Yutaka Hayashi at the ETL in 1984.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] They demonstrated that short-channel effects can be significantly reduced by sandwiching a fully depleted silicon-on-insulator (SOI) device between two gate electrodes connected together.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The first FinFET transistor type was called a *depleted lean-channel transistor* (DELTA) transistor, which was first fabricated in Japan by Hitachi Central Research Laboratory's Digh Hisamoto, Toru Kaga, Yoshifumi Kawamoto and Eiji Takeda in 1989.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The gate of the transistor can cover and electrically contact the semiconductor channel fin on both the top and the sides or only on the sides.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The former is called a *tri-gate transistor* and the latter a *double-gate transistor*.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] A double-gate transistor optionally can have each side connected to two different terminal or contacts.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] This variant is called *split transistor,* enabling more refined control of the operation of the transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Indonesian engineer Effendi Leobandung, while working at the University of Minnesota, published a paper with Stephen Y.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Chou at the 54th Device Research Conference in 1996 outlining the benefit of cutting a wide CMOS transistor into many channels with narrow width to improve device scaling and increase device current by increasing the effective device width.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] This structure is what a modern FinFET looks like.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Although some device width is sacrificed by cutting it into narrow widths, the conduction of the side wall of narrow fins more than make up for the loss, for tall fins.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The device had a 35 nm channel width and 70 nm channel length.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA), in 1997 awarded a contract to a research group at the University of California, Berkeley to develop a practical 3D sub-micron FinFET technology.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The group was led by Hisamoto along with TSMC's Chenming Hu.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The team made the following breakthroughs between 1998 and 2004.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Digh Hisamoto requested to be a visiting researcher in Chenming Hu's Berkeley research group.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Chenming Hu invited Hisamoto to join the DARPA funded FinFET project.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] They coined the term "FinFET" (fin field-effect transistor) in a December 2000 paper, used to describe a non-planar, double-gate transistor built on an SOI substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2006, a team of Korean researchers from the Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (KAIST) and the National Nano Fab Center developed a 3 nm transistor, the world's smallest nanoelectronic device, based on gate-all-around (GAA) FinFET technology.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2011, Rice University researchers Masoud Rostami and Kartik Mohanram demonstrated that FinFETs can have two electrically independent gates, which gives circuit designers more flexibility to design with efficient, low-power gates.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2020, Chenming Hu received the IEEE Medal of Honor award for his development of the FinFET, which the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) credited with taking transistors to the third dimension and extending Moore's law.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The industry's first 25 nanometer transistor operating on just 0.7 volts was demonstrated in December 2002 by TSMC.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] The "Omega FinFET" design, named after the similarity between the Greek letter "Omega" and the shape in which the gate wraps around the source/drain structure, has a gate delay of just 0.39 picosecond (ps) for the N-type transistor and 0.88 ps for the P-type.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2004, Samsung demonstrated a "bulk FinFET" design, which made it possible to mass-produce FinFET devices.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] They demonstrated dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) manufactured with a 90 nm bulk FinFET process.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2011, Intel demonstrated tri-gate transistors, where the gate surrounds the channel on three sides, allowing for increased energy efficiency and lower gate delay—and thus greater performance—over planar transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Commercially produced chips at 22 nm and below have generally utilised FinFET gate designs (but planar processes do exist down to 18 nm, with 12 nm in development).
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Intel's tri-gate variant were announced at 22 nm in 2011 for its Ivy Bridge microarchitecture.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] These devices shipped from 2012 onwards.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] From 2014 onwards, at 14 nm (or 16 nm) major foundries (TSMC, Samsung, GlobalFoundries) utilised FinFET designs.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2013, SK Hynix began commercial mass-production of a 16 nm process, TSMC began production of a 16 nm FinFET process, and Samsung Electronics began production of a 10 nm process.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] TSMC began production of a 7 nm process in 2017, and Samsung began production of a 5 nm process in 2018.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2019, Samsung announced plans for the commercial production of a 3 nm GAAFET process by 2021.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] FD-SOI (fully depleted silicon on insulator) has been seen as a potential low cost alternative to FinFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] Commercial production of nanoelectronic FinFET semiconductor memory began in the 2010s.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2013, SK Hynix began mass-production of 16 nm NAND flash memory, and Samsung Electronics began production of 10 nm multi-level cell (MLC) NAND flash memory.
[src:cmos-technology/finfet] In 2017, TSMC began production of SRAM memory using a 7 nm process.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In electronics, the **metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor** (**MOSFET**, **MOS-FET**, **MOS FET**, or **MOS transistor**) is a type of field-effect transistor (FET), most commonly fabricated by the controlled oxidation of silicon.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] It has an insulated gate, the voltage of which determines the conductivity of the device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This ability to change conductivity with the amount of applied voltage can be used for amplifying or switching electronic signals.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The term *metal–insulator–semiconductor field-effect transistor* (*MISFET*) is almost synonymous with *MOSFET*.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Another near-synonym is *insulated-gate field-effect transistor* (*IGFET*).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Physicist Julius Edgar Lilienfeld first proposed the concept of a field-effect transistor (FET) in 1925, but it was not possible to construct a working device at that time.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The first working metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) was invented in 1959 by engineers Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng at Bell Labs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Their breakthrough—fabricating a practical field-effect transistor enabled by Atalla’s earlier work on silicon surface passivation and thermal oxidation—revolutionized electronics and paved the way for smaller and cheaper radios, calculators, computers, and other electronic devices.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The main advantage of a MOSFET is that it requires almost no input current to control the load current under steady-state or low-frequency conditions, especially compared to bipolar junction transistors (BJTs).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] However, at high frequencies or when switching rapidly, a MOSFET may require significant current to charge and discharge its gate capacitance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In an *enhancement mode* MOSFET, voltage applied to the gate terminal increases the conductivity of the device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In *depletion mode* transistors, voltage applied at the gate reduces the conductivity.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The "metal" in the name MOSFET is sometimes a misnomer, because the gate material can be a layer of polysilicon (polycrystalline silicon).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Similarly, "oxide" in the name can also be a misnomer, as different dielectric materials are used with the aim of obtaining strong channels with smaller applied voltages.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The MOSFET is by far the most common transistor in digital circuits, as billions may be included in a memory chip or microprocessor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] As MOSFETs can be made with either a p-type or n-type channel, complementary pairs of MOS transistors can be used to make switching circuits with very low power consumption, in the form of CMOS logic.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The basic principle of the field-effect transistor was first filed as a patent by Julius Edgar Lilienfeld as a Canadian patent in 1925 and later as a U.S. patent in 1926.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In 1934, inventor Oskar Heil independently patented a similar device in Europe.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the 1940s, Bell Labs scientists William Shockley, John Bardeen and Walter Houser Brattain attempted to build a field-effect device which led to their discovery of the transistor effect.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] However, their structure failed to show the anticipated effects due to the problem of surface states: traps on the semiconductor surface that hold electrons immobile.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] With no surface passivation they were only able to build the BJT and thyristor transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] By 1957 Frosch and Derick, using masking and predeposition, were able to manufacture silicon dioxide field effect transistors; the first planar transistors, in which drain and source were adjacent at the same surface.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] They showed that silicon dioxide insulated, protected silicon wafers and prevented dopants from diffusing into the wafer.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] At Bell Labs, the importance of Frosch and Derick technique and transistors was immediately realized.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Results of their work circulated around Bell Labs in the form of BTL memos before being published in 1957.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] At Shockley Semiconductor, Shockley had circulated the preprint of their article in December 1956 to all his senior staff, including Jean Hoerni, who would later invent the planar process in 1959 while at Fairchild Semiconductor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Spitzer studied the mechanism of thermally grown oxides, fabricated a high quality Si/SiO2 stack and published their results in 1960.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This was a culmination of decades of field-effect research that began with Lilienfeld.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The first MOS transistor at Bell Labs was about 100 times slower than contemporary bipolar transistors and was initially seen as inferior.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Nevertheless, Kahng pointed out several advantages of the device, notably ease of fabrication and its application in integrated circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Many semiconductors with better electrical properties than silicon, such as gallium arsenide, do not form good semiconductor-to-insulator interfaces, and thus are not suitable for MOSFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Research continues on creating insulators with acceptable electrical characteristics on other semiconductor materials.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] To overcome the increase in power consumption due to gate current leakage, a high-κ dielectric is used instead of silicon dioxide for the gate insulator, while polysilicon is replaced by metal gates (e.g.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The gate is separated from the channel by a thin insulating layer, traditionally of silicon dioxide and later of silicon oxynitride.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Some companies use a high-κ dielectric and metal gate combination in the 45 nanometer node.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When a voltage is applied between the gate and the source, the electric field generated penetrates through the oxide and creates an *inversion layer* or *channel* at the semiconductor-insulator interface.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The inversion layer provides a channel through which current can pass between source and drain terminals.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Varying the voltage between the gate and body modulates the conductivity of this layer and thereby controls the current flow between drain and source.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The traditional metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) structure is obtained by growing a layer of silicon dioxide (SiO 2) on top of a silicon substrate, commonly by thermal oxidation and depositing a layer of metal or polycrystalline silicon (the latter is commonly used).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] As silicon dioxide is a dielectric material, its structure is equivalent to a planar capacitor, with one of the electrodes replaced by a semiconductor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When a voltage is applied across a MOS structure, it modifies the distribution of charges in the semiconductor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If *V*G is high enough, a high concentration of negative charge carriers forms in an *inversion layer* located in a thin layer next to the interface between the semiconductor and the insulator.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Conventionally, the gate voltage at which the volume density of electrons in the inversion layer is the same as the volume density of holes in the body is called the threshold voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When the voltage between transistor gate and source (*V*G) exceeds the threshold voltage (*V*th), the difference is known as overdrive voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This structure with p-type body is the basis of the n-type MOSFET, which requires the addition of n-type source and drain regions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The MOS capacitor structure is the heart of the MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Consider a MOS capacitor where the silicon base is of p-type.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If a positive voltage is applied at the gate, holes which are at the surface of the p-type substrate will be repelled by the electric field generated by the voltage applied.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] At first, the holes will simply be repelled and what will remain on the surface will be immobile (negative) atoms of the acceptor type, which creates a depletion region on the surface.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] A hole is created by an acceptor atom, e.g., boron, which has one less electron than a silicon atom.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Holes are not actually repelled, being non-entities; electrons are attracted by the positive field, and fill these holes.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This creates a depletion region where no charge carriers exist because the electron is now fixed onto the atom and immobile.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] As the voltage at the gate increases, there will be a point at which the surface above the depletion region will be converted from p-type into n-type, as electrons from the bulk area will start to get attracted by the larger electric field.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The threshold voltage at which this conversion happens is one of the most important parameters in a MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the case of a p-type MOSFET, bulk inversion happens when the intrinsic energy level at the surface becomes smaller than the Fermi level at the surface.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The Fermi level defines the type of semiconductor in discussion.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the Fermi level is equal to the Intrinsic level, the semiconductor is of intrinsic, or pure type.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the Fermi level lies closer to the conduction band (valence band) then the semiconductor type will be of n-type (p-type).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When the gate voltage is increased in a positive sense (for the given example), this will shift the intrinsic energy level band so that it will curve downwards towards the valence band.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the Fermi level lies closer to the valence band (for p-type), there will be a point when the Intrinsic level will start to cross the Fermi level and when the voltage reaches the threshold voltage, the intrinsic level does cross the Fermi level, and that is what is known as inversion.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] At that point, the surface of the semiconductor is inverted from p-type into n-type.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] A MOSFET is based on the modulation of charge concentration by a MOS capacitance between a *body* electrode and a *gate* electrode located above the body and insulated from all other device regions by a gate dielectric layer.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If dielectrics other than an oxide are employed, the device may be referred to as a metal-insulator-semiconductor FET (MISFET).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Compared to the MOS capacitor, the MOSFET includes two additional terminals (*source* and *drain*), each connected to individual highly doped regions that are separated by the body region.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] These regions can be either p or n type, but they must both be of the same type, and of opposite type to the body region.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The source and drain (unlike the body) are highly doped as signified by a "+" sign after the type of doping.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the MOSFET is an n-channel or nMOS FET, then the source and drain are *n+* regions and the body is a *p* region.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the MOSFET is a p-channel or pMOS FET, then the source and drain are *p+* regions and the body is a *n* region.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The source is so named because it is the source of the charge carriers (electrons for n-channel, holes for p-channel) that flow through the channel; similarly, the drain is where the charge carriers leave the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The occupancy of the energy bands in a semiconductor is set by the position of the Fermi level relative to the semiconductor energy-band edges.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] With sufficient gate voltage, the valence band edge is driven far from the Fermi level, and holes from the body are driven away from the gate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] At larger gate bias still, near the semiconductor surface the conduction band edge is brought close to the Fermi level, populating the surface with electrons in an *inversion layer* or *n-channel* at the interface between the p region and the oxide.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This conducting channel extends between the source and the drain, and current is conducted through it when a voltage is applied between the two electrodes.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Increasing the voltage on the gate leads to a higher electron density in the inversion layer and therefore increases the current flow between the source and drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For gate voltages below the threshold value, the channel is lightly populated, and only a very small subthreshold leakage current can flow between the source and the drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When a negative gate-source voltage (positive source-gate) is applied, it creates a *p-channel* at the surface of the n region, analogous to the n-channel case, but with opposite polarities of charges and voltages.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When a voltage less negative than the threshold value (a negative voltage for the p-channel) is applied between gate and source, the channel disappears and only a very small subthreshold current can flow between the source and the drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The device may comprise a silicon on insulator device in which a buried oxide is formed below a thin semiconductor layer.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the channel region between the gate dielectric and the buried oxide region is very thin, the channel is referred to as an ultrathin channel region with the source and drain regions formed on either side in or above the thin semiconductor layer.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Other semiconductor materials may be employed.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When the source and drain regions are formed above the channel in whole or in part, they are referred to as raised source/drain regions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The operation of a MOSFET can be separated into three different modes, depending on the device's threshold voltage ( $V_{\text{th}}$ ), gate-to-source voltage ( $V_{\text{GS}}$ ), and drain-to-source voltage ( $V_{\text{DS}}$ ).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the following discussion, a simplified algebraic model is used.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Modern MOSFET characteristics are more complex than the algebraic model presented here.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] According to the basic threshold model, the transistor is turned off, and there is no conduction between drain and source.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] A more accurate model considers the effect of thermal energy on the Fermi–Dirac distribution of electron energies which allow some of the more energetic electrons at the source to enter the channel and flow to the drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This results in a subthreshold current that is an exponential function of gate-source voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] While the current between drain and source should ideally be zero when the transistor is being used as a turned-off switch, there is a weak-inversion current, sometimes called subthreshold leakage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] where $C_{\text{dep}}$ is the capacitance of the depletion layer and $C_{\text{ox}}$ is the capacitance of the oxide layer.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This equation is generally used, but is only an adequate approximation for the source tied to the bulk.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Frequently, threshold voltage *V*th for this mode is defined as the gate voltage at which a selected value of current *I*D0 occurs, for example, *I*D0 = 1 μA, which may not be the same *V*th-value used in the equations for the following modes.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Some micropower analog circuits are designed to take advantage of subthreshold conduction.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] By working in the weak-inversion region, the MOSFETs in these circuits deliver the highest possible transconductance-to-current ratio, namely: $g_{m}/I_{\text{D}}=1/\left(nV_{\text{T}}\right)$ , almost that of a bipolar transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The resulting sensitivity to fabricational variations complicates optimization for leakage and performance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The transistor is turned on, and a channel has been created which allows current between the drain and the source.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The MOSFET operates like a resistor, controlled by the gate voltage relative to both the source and drain voltages.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] where $\mu _{n}$ is the charge-carrier effective mobility, W is the gate width, L is the gate length and $C_{\text{ox}}$ is the gate oxide capacitance per unit area.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The transition from the exponential subthreshold region to the triode region is not as sharp as the equations suggest.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The switch is turned on, and a channel has been created, which allows current between the drain and source.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Since the drain voltage is higher than the source voltage, the electrons spread out, and conduction is not through a narrow channel but through a broader, two- or three-dimensional current distribution extending away from the interface and deeper in the substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The onset of this region is also known as pinch-off to indicate the lack of channel region near the drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Although the channel does not extend the full length of the device, the electric field between the drain and the channel is very high, and conduction continues.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The additional factor involving λ, the channel-length modulation parameter, models current dependence on drain voltage due to the Early effect, or channel length modulation.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] where the combination *V*ov = *V*GS − *V*th is called the overdrive voltage, and where *V*DSsat = *V*GS − *V*th accounts for a small discontinuity in $I_{\text{D}}$ which would otherwise appear at the transition between the triode and saturation regions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] *I*D is the expression in the saturation region.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If λ is taken as zero, an infinite output resistance of the device results that leads to unrealistic circuit predictions, particularly in analog circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] As the channel length becomes very short, these equations become quite inaccurate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For example, carrier transport in the active mode may become limited by velocity saturation.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When velocity saturation dominates, the saturation drain current is more nearly linear than quadratic in *V*GS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] At even shorter lengths, carriers transport with near zero scattering, known as quasi-ballistic transport.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the ballistic regime, the carriers travel at an injection velocity that may exceed the saturation velocity and approaches the Fermi velocity at high inversion charge density.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In addition, drain-induced barrier lowering increases off-state (cutoff) current and requires an increase in threshold voltage to compensate, which in turn reduces the saturation current.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Application of a source-to-substrate reverse bias of the source-body pn-junction introduces a split between the Fermi levels for electrons and holes, moving the Fermi level for the channel further from the band edge, lowering the occupancy of the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The effect is to increase the gate voltage necessary to establish the channel, as seen in the figure.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This change in channel strength by application of reverse bias is called the "body effect".
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Using an nMOS example, the gate-to-body bias *V*GB positions the conduction-band energy levels, while the source-to-body bias VSB positions the electron Fermi level near the interface, deciding occupancy of these levels near the interface, and hence the strength of the inversion layer or channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] As this equation shows, a reverse bias *V*SB > 0 causes an increase in threshold voltage *V*TB and therefore demands a larger gate voltage before the channel populates.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The body can be operated as a second gate, and is sometimes referred to as the "back gate"; the body effect is sometimes called the "back-gate effect".
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] A variety of symbols are used for the MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The basic design is generally a line for the channel with the source and drain leaving it at right angles and then bending back at right angles into the same direction as the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Sometimes three line segments are used for enhancement mode and a solid line for depletion mode (see depletion and enhancement modes).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Another line is drawn parallel to the channel for the gate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The *bulk* or *body* connection, if shown, is shown connected to the back of the channel with an arrow indicating pMOS or nMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This arrow always points from P to N, so an nMOS (N-channel in P-well or P-substrate) has the arrow pointing from the bulk to the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Typically the bulk is internally connected to the source (as is generally the case with discrete devices), in which case the bulk end of the arrow will have a line drawn between it and the source to explicitly show this connection.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Some symbols will also explicitly show the MOSFET's *intrinsic body diode* along an outer (and sometimes dotted, as may be done for parasitic elements) path between drain and source.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Note that tying the bulk to the source is by no means the only important configuration.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In general, the MOSFET is a four-terminal device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In integrated circuits, many of the MOSFETs share a body connection, not necessarily connected to the source terminals of all the transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] If the bulk is not shown (as is often the case in IC design as they are generally common bulk) an inversion symbol is sometimes used to indicate pMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Alternatively, as is done with bipolar transistors, an arrow on the MOSFET's source may indicate the direction of conventional current: pointing out for nMOS, in for pMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In schematics where G, S, D are not labeled, the detailed features of the symbol indicate which terminal is source and which is drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For enhancement-mode and depletion-mode MOSFET symbols (in columns two and five), the source terminal is the one connected to the triangle.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Additionally, in this diagram, the gate is shown as an "L" shape, whose input leg is closer to S than D, also indicating which is which.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] However, these symbols are often drawn with a T-shaped gate (as elsewhere on this page), so it is the triangle which must be relied upon to indicate the source terminal.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Digital integrated circuits such as microprocessors and memory devices contain thousands to billions of integrated MOSFETs on each device, providing the basic switching functions required to implement logic gates and data storage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Discrete devices are widely used in applications such as switch mode power supplies, variable-frequency drives and other power electronics applications where each device may be switching thousands of watts.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Radio-frequency amplifiers up to the UHF spectrum use MOSFET transistors as analog signal and power amplifiers.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Radio systems also use MOSFETs as oscillators, or mixers to convert frequencies.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Largely because of these two factors, the MOSFET has become the most widely used type of transistor in the Institution of Engineering and Technology (IET).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] General Micro-electronics introduced the first commercial MOS integrated circuit in 1964.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Additionally, the method of coupling two complementary MOSFETs (P-channel and N-channel) into one high/low switch, known as CMOS, means that digital circuits dissipate very little power except when actually switched.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The earliest microprocessors starting in 1970 were all MOS microprocessors, fabricated entirely from PMOS logic or fabricated entirely from nMOS logic.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the 1970s, MOS microprocessors were often contrasted with CMOS microprocessors and bipolar bit-slice processors.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The MOSFET is used in digital complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) logic, which uses p- and n-channel MOSFETs as building blocks.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Overheating is a major concern in integrated circuits since ever more transistors are packed into ever smaller chips.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] CMOS logic reduces power consumption because no current flows (ideally), and thus no power is consumed, except when the inputs to logic gates are being switched.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] CMOS accomplishes this current reduction by complementing every nMOS FET with a pMOS FET and connecting both gates and both drains together.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] A high voltage on the gates will cause the nMOS FET to conduct and the pMOS FET not to conduct and a low voltage on the gates causes the reverse.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] During the switching time as the voltage goes from one state to another, both MOSFETs will conduct briefly.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The growth of digital technologies like the microprocessor has provided the motivation to advance MOSFET technology faster than any other type of silicon-based transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] A big advantage of MOSFETs for digital switching is that the oxide layer between the gate and the channel prevents DC current from flowing through the gate, further reducing power consumption and giving a very large input impedance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The insulating oxide between the gate and channel effectively isolates a MOSFET in one logic stage from earlier and later stages, which allows a single MOSFET output to drive a considerable number of MOSFET inputs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Bipolar transistor-based logic (such as TTL) does not have such a high fanout capacity.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This isolation also makes it easier for the designers to ignore to some extent loading effects between logic stages independently.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] That extent is defined by the operating frequency: as frequencies increase, the input impedance of the MOSFETs decreases.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The MOSFET's advantages in digital circuits do not translate into supremacy in all analog circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The two types of circuit draw upon different features of transistor behavior.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Digital circuits switch, spending most of their time either fully on or fully off.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The transition from one to the other is only of concern with regards to speed and charge required.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Analog circuits depend on operation in the transition region where small changes to *V*gs can modulate the output (drain) current.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The JFET and bipolar junction transistor (BJT) are preferred for accurate matching (of adjacent devices in integrated circuits), higher transconductance and certain temperature characteristics which simplify keeping performance predictable as circuit temperature varies.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Nevertheless, MOSFETs are widely used in many types of analog circuits because of their own advantages (zero gate current, high and adjustable output impedance and improved robustness vs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] BJTs which can be permanently degraded by even lightly breaking down the emitter-base).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The characteristics and performance of many analog circuits can be scaled up or down by changing the sizes (length and width) of the MOSFETs used.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] By comparison, bipolar transistors follow a different scaling law.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] MOSFETs' ideal characteristics regarding gate current (zero) and drain-source offset voltage (zero) also make them nearly ideal switch elements, and also make switched capacitor analog circuits practical.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In their linear region, MOSFETs can be used as precision resistors, which can have a much higher controlled resistance than BJTs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In high power circuits, MOSFETs sometimes have the advantage of not suffering from thermal runaway as BJTs do.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This means that complete analog circuits can be made on a silicon chip in a much smaller space and with simpler fabrication techniques.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] MOSFETS are ideally suited to switch inductive loads because of tolerance to inductive kickback.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Some ICs combine analog and digital MOSFET circuitry on a single mixed-signal integrated circuit, making the needed board space even smaller.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This creates a need to isolate the analog circuits from the digital circuits on a chip level, leading to the use of isolation rings and silicon on insulator (SOI).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Since MOSFETs require more space to handle a given amount of power than a BJT, fabrication processes can incorporate BJTs and MOSFETs into a single device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Mixed-transistor devices are called bi-FETs (bipolar FETs) if they contain just one BJT-FET and BiCMOS (bipolar-CMOS) if they contain complementary BJT-FETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Such devices have the advantages of both insulated gates and higher current density.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Bidirectional analog switches pass analog signals when on or block them (by presenting a high impedance) when off.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The MOSFETs used are typically symmetrical, such that their drain and source exchange places depending on the relative voltages of their electrodes; at any moment, the source would be the more negative side for an nMOS or the more positive side for a pMOS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] All of these switches are limited on what signals they can pass or stop by their gate-source, gate-drain and source–drain voltages; exceeding the voltage, current, or power limits will potentially damage the switch.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This analog switch uses a four-terminal symmetrical MOSFET of either P or N type.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the case of an n-type switch, the body is connected to the most negative supply (usually GND) and the gate is used as the switch control.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Whenever the gate voltage exceeds the source voltage by at least a threshold voltage, the MOSFET conducts.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The higher the voltage, the more the MOSFET can conduct.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] An nMOS switch passes all voltages less than Vgate − *V*threshold_nMOS, but passes lower voltages better than higher ones.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When the switch is conducting, it typically operates in the linear (or ohmic) mode of operation, since the source and drain voltages will typically be nearly equal.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the case of a pMOS, the body is connected to the most positive voltage, and the gate is brought to a lower potential to turn the switch on.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The pMOS switch passes all voltages higher than Vgate − *V*threshold_pMOS (note: enhancement-mode pMOS FETs have a negative threshold voltage), but passes higher voltages better than lower ones.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This "complementary" or CMOS type of switch uses one pMOS and one nMOS FET connected in parallel to counteract the limitations of the single-type switch.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] When used in digital logic it is called a transmission gate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The FETs have their drains and sources connected in parallel, the body of the pMOS is connected to the high potential (Vpos in diagram) and the body of the nMOS is connected to the low potential (Vneg).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] To turn the switch on, the gate of the pMOS is driven to the low potential and the gate of the nMOS is driven to the high potential.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For voltages between Vpos − *V*threshold_nMOS and Vneg − *V*threshold_pMOS, both FETs conduct the signal, though with the nMOS passing lower voltages better while the pMOS passes higher voltages better.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For voltages less than Vneg − *V*threshold_pMOS, the nMOS conducts alone.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For voltages greater than Vpos − *V*threshold_nMOS, the pMOS conducts alone.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The voltage limits for this switch are the gate-source, gate-drain and source-drain voltage limits for both FETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Also, the pMOS is typically two to three times wider than the nMOS, so the switch will be balanced for speed in the two directions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Tri-state circuitry sometimes incorporates a CMOS MOSFET switch on its output to provide for a low-ohmic, full-range output when on, and a high-ohmic, mid-level signal when off.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The primary criterion for the gate material is that it is a good conductor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Highly doped polycrystalline silicon is an acceptable but certainly not ideal conductor, and also suffers from some more technical deficiencies in its role as the standard gate material.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The silicon-SiO2 interface has been well studied and is known to have relatively few defects.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] By contrast many metal-insulator interfaces contain significant levels of defects which can lead to Fermi level pinning, charging, or other phenomena that ultimately degrade device performance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In the MOSFET IC fabrication process, it is preferable to deposit the gate material prior to certain high-temperature steps in order to make better-performing transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Such high temperature steps would melt some metals, limiting the types of metal that can be used in a metal-gate-based process.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] While polysilicon gates have been the de facto standard for the last twenty years, they do have some disadvantages which have led to their likely future replacement by metal gates.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] Present high performance CPUs use metal gate technology, together with high-κ dielectrics, a combination known as *high-κ, metal gate* (HKMG).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] High-κ dielectrics are now well studied, and their defects are understood.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] HKMG processes exist that do not require the metals to experience high temperature anneals; other processes select metals that can survive the annealing step.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] As devices are made smaller, insulating layers are made thinner, often through steps of thermal oxidation or localised oxidation of silicon (LOCOS).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] For nano-scaled devices, at some point tunneling of carriers through the insulator from the channel to the gate electrode takes place.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] To reduce the resulting leakage current, the insulator can be made thinner by choosing a material with a higher dielectric constant.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] with *Q* = charge density, κ = dielectric constant, ε0 = permittivity of empty space and *E* = electric field.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] From this law it appears the same charge can be maintained in the channel at a lower field provided κ is increased.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] with *V*G = gate voltage, *V*ch = voltage at channel side of insulator, and *t*ins = insulator thickness.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] This equation shows the gate voltage will not increase when the insulator thickness increases, provided κ increases to keep *t*ins / κ = constant (see the article on high-κ dielectrics for more detail, and the section in this article on gate-oxide leakage).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The insulator in a MOSFET is a dielectric which can in any event be silicon oxide, formed by LOCOS but many other dielectric materials are employed.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The generic term for the dielectric is gate dielectric since the dielectric lies directly below the gate electrode and above the channel of the MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The drain induced barrier lowering of the threshold voltage and channel length modulation effects upon *I-V* curves are reduced by using shallow junction extensions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] In addition, *halo* doping can be used, that is, the addition of very thin heavily doped regions of the same doping type as the body tight against the junction walls to limit the extent of depletion regions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] The capacitive effects are limited by using raised source and drain geometries that make most of the contact area border thick dielectric instead of silicon.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p01] These various features of junction design are shown (with artistic license) in the figure.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Over the past decades, the MOSFET (as used for digital logic) has continually been scaled down in size; typical MOSFET channel lengths were once several micrometres, but modern integrated circuits are incorporating MOSFETs with channel lengths of tens of nanometers.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Robert Dennard's work on scaling theory was pivotal in recognising that this ongoing reduction was possible.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Intel began production of a process featuring a 32 nm feature size (with the channel being even shorter) in late 2009.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The semiconductor industry maintains a "roadmap", the ITRS, which sets the pace for MOSFET development.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Smaller MOSFETs are desirable for several reasons.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The main reason to make transistors smaller is to pack more and more devices in a given chip area.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] This results in a chip with the same functionality in a smaller area, or chips with more functionality in the same area.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Since fabrication costs for a semiconductor wafer are relatively fixed, the cost per integrated circuits is mainly related to the number of chips that can be produced per wafer.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Hence, smaller ICs allow more chips per wafer, reducing the price per chip.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] In fact, over the past 30 years the number of transistors per chip has been doubled every 2–3 years once a new technology node is introduced.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] For example, the number of MOSFETs in a microprocessor fabricated in a 45 nm technology can well be twice as many as in a 65 nm chip.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] This doubling of transistor density was first observed by Gordon Moore in 1965 and is commonly referred to as Moore's law.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] It is also expected that smaller transistors switch faster.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] For example, one approach to size reduction is a scaling of the MOSFET that requires all device dimensions to reduce proportionally.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The main device dimensions are the channel length, channel width, and oxide thickness.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] When they are scaled down by equal factors, the transistor channel resistance does not change, while gate capacitance is cut by that factor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Hence, the RC delay of the transistor scales with a similar factor.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] While this has been traditionally the case for the older technologies, for the state-of-the-art MOSFETs reduction of the transistor dimensions does not necessarily translate to higher chip speed because the delay due to interconnections is more significant.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Producing MOSFETs with channel lengths much smaller than a micrometre is a challenge, and the difficulties of semiconductor device fabrication are always a limiting factor in advancing integrated circuit technology.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As MOSFET geometries shrink, the voltage that can be applied to the gate must be reduced to maintain reliability.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] To maintain performance, the threshold voltage of the MOSFET has to be reduced as well.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Subthreshold leakage (including subthreshold conduction, gate-oxide leakage and reverse-biased junction leakage), which was ignored in the past, now can consume upwards of half of the total power consumption of modern high-performance VLSI chips.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The gate oxide, which serves as insulator between the gate and channel, should be made as thin as possible to increase the channel conductivity and performance when the transistor is on and to reduce subthreshold leakage when the transistor is off.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] However, with current gate oxides with a thickness of around 1.2 nm (which in silicon is ~5 atoms thick) the quantum mechanical phenomenon of electron tunneling occurs between the gate and channel, leading to increased power consumption.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Silicon dioxide has traditionally been used as the gate insulator.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Silicon dioxide however has a modest dielectric constant.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Increasing the dielectric constant of the gate dielectric allows a thicker layer while maintaining a high capacitance (capacitance is proportional to dielectric constant and inversely proportional to dielectric thickness).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] All else equal, a higher dielectric thickness reduces the quantum tunneling current through the dielectric between the gate and the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Insulators that have a larger dielectric constant than silicon dioxide (referred to as high-κ dielectrics), such as group IVb metal silicates e.g. hafnium and zirconium silicates and oxides are being used to reduce the gate leakage from the 45 nanometer technology node onwards.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] On the other hand, the barrier height of the new gate insulator is an important consideration; the difference in conduction band energy between the semiconductor and the dielectric (and the corresponding difference in valence band energy) also affects leakage current level.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] For the traditional gate oxide, silicon dioxide, the former barrier is approximately 8 eV.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] For many alternative dielectrics the value is significantly lower, tending to increase the tunneling current, somewhat negating the advantage of higher dielectric constant.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The maximum gate-source voltage is determined by the strength of the electric field able to be sustained by the gate dielectric before significant leakage occurs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As the insulating dielectric is made thinner, the electric field strength within it goes up for a fixed voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] This necessitates using lower voltages with the thinner dielectric.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] To make devices smaller, junction design has become more complex, leading to higher doping levels, shallower junctions, "halo" doping and so forth, all to decrease drain-induced barrier lowering (see the section on junction design).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] To keep these complex junctions in place, the annealing steps formerly used to remove damage and electrically active defects must be curtailed increasing junction leakage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Heavier doping is also associated with thinner depletion layers and more recombination centers that result in increased leakage current, even without lattice damage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Drain-induced barrier lowering (DIBL) and *V*T roll off: Because of the short-channel effect, channel formation is not entirely done by the gate, but now the drain and source also affect the channel formation.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As the channel length decreases, the depletion regions of the source and drain come closer together and make the threshold voltage (*V*T) a function of the length of the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] *V*T also becomes function of drain to source voltage *V*DS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As we increase the *V*DS, the depletion regions increase in size, and a considerable amount of charge is depleted by the *V*DS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The gate voltage required to form the channel is then lowered, and thus, the *V*T decreases with an increase in *V*DS.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] This effect is called drain induced barrier lowering (DIBL).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] For analog operation, good gain requires a high MOSFET output impedance, which is to say, the MOSFET current should vary only slightly with the applied drain-to-source voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As devices are made smaller, the influence of the drain competes more successfully with that of the gate due to the growing proximity of these two electrodes, increasing the sensitivity of the MOSFET current to the drain voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] To counteract the resulting decrease in output resistance, circuits are made more complex, either by requiring more devices, for example the cascode and cascade amplifiers, or by feedback circuitry using operational amplifiers, for example a circuit like that in the adjacent figure.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The transconductance of the MOSFET decides its gain and is proportional to hole or electron mobility (depending on device type), at least for low drain voltages.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As MOSFET size is reduced, the fields in the channel increase and the dopant impurity levels increase.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Both changes reduce the carrier mobility, and hence the transconductance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As channel lengths are reduced without proportional reduction in drain voltage, raising the electric field in the channel, the result is velocity saturation of the carriers, limiting the current and the transconductance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Traditionally, switching time was roughly proportional to the gate capacitance of gates.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] However, with transistors becoming smaller and more transistors being placed on the chip, interconnect capacitance (the capacitance of the metal-layer connections between different parts of the chip) is becoming a large percentage of capacitance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Signals have to travel through the interconnect, which leads to increased delay and lower performance.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The ever-increasing density of MOSFETs on an integrated circuit creates problems of substantial localized heat generation that can impair circuit operation.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Circuits operate more slowly at high temperatures, and have reduced reliability and shorter lifetimes.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Heat sinks and other cooling devices and methods are now required for many integrated circuits including microprocessors.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Power MOSFETs are at risk of thermal runaway.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As their on-state resistance rises with temperature, if the load is approximately a constant-current load then the power loss rises correspondingly, generating further heat.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] When the heatsink is not able to keep the temperature low enough, the junction temperature may rise quickly and uncontrollably, resulting in destruction of the device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] With MOSFETs becoming smaller, the number of atoms in the silicon that produce many of the transistor's properties is becoming fewer, with the result that control of dopant numbers and placement is more erratic.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] During chip manufacturing, random process variations affect all transistor dimensions: length, width, junction depths, oxide thickness *etc.*, and become a greater percentage of overall transistor size as the transistor shrinks.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The transistor characteristics become less certain, more statistical.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The random nature of manufacture means we do not know which particular example MOSFETs actually will end up in a particular instance of the circuit.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] This uncertainty forces a less optimal design because the design must work for a great variety of possible component MOSFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] See process variation, design for manufacturability, reliability engineering, and statistical process control.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Modern ICs are computer-simulated with the goal of obtaining working circuits from the first manufactured lot.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As devices are miniaturized, the complexity of the processing makes it difficult to predict exactly what the final devices look like, and modeling of physical processes becomes more challenging as well.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] In addition, microscopic variations in structure due simply to the probabilistic nature of atomic processes require statistical (not just deterministic) predictions.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] These factors combine to make adequate simulation and "right the first time" manufacture difficult.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The dual-gate MOSFET has a tetrode configuration, where both gates control the current in the device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] It is commonly used for small-signal devices in radio frequency applications where biasing the drain-side gate at constant potential reduces the gain loss caused by Miller effect, replacing two separate transistors in cascode configuration.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Other common uses in RF circuits include gain control and mixing (frequency conversion).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The *tetrode* description, though accurate, does not replicate the vacuum-tube tetrode.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Vacuum-tube tetrodes, using a screen grid, exhibit much lower grid-plate capacitance and much higher output impedance and voltage gains than triode vacuum tubes.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] These improvements are commonly an order of magnitude (10 times) or considerably more.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Tetrode transistors (whether bipolar junction or field-effect) do not exhibit improvements of such a great degree.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The FinFET is a double-gate silicon-on-insulator device, one of a number of geometries being introduced to mitigate the effects of short channels and reduce drain-induced barrier lowering.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The *fin* refers to the narrow channel between source and drain.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] A thin insulating oxide layer on either side of the fin separates it from the gate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] SOI FinFETs with a thick oxide on top of the fin are called *double-gate* and those with a thin oxide on top as well as on the sides are called *triple-gate* FinFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] There are *depletion-mode* MOSFET devices, which are less commonly used than the standard *enhancement-mode* devices already described.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] These are MOSFET devices that are doped so that a channel exists even with zero voltage from gate to source.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] To control the channel, a negative voltage is applied to the gate (for an n-channel device), depleting the channel, which reduces the current flow through the device.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] In essence, the depletion-mode device is equivalent to a normally closed (on) switch, while the enhancement-mode device is equivalent to a normally open (off) switch.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Due to their low noise figure in the RF region, and better gain, these devices are often preferred to bipolars in RF front-ends such as in TV sets.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Depletion-mode MOSFET families include the BF960 by Siemens and Telefunken, and the BF980 in the 1980s by Philips (later to become NXP Semiconductors), whose derivatives are still used in AGC and RF mixer front-ends.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Metal–insulator–semiconductor field-effect-transistor, or *MISFET*, is a more general term than *MOSFET* and a synonym to *insulated-gate field-effect transistor* (IGFET).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] All MOSFETs are MISFETs, but not all MISFETs are MOSFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The gate dielectric insulator in a MISFET is a substrate oxide (hence typically silicon dioxide) in a MOSFET, but other materials can also be employed.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The gate dielectric lies directly below the gate electrode and above the channel of the MISFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The term *metal* is historically used for the gate material, even though now it is usually highly doped polysilicon or some other non-metal.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] These were the driving principles in the design of nMOS logic which uses n-channel MOSFETs exclusively.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] However, neglecting leakage current, unlike CMOS logic, nMOS logic consumes power even when no switching is taking place.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] With advances in technology, CMOS logic displaced nMOS logic in the mid-1980s to become the preferred process for digital chips.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Power MOSFETs have a different structure.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] As with most power devices, the structure is vertical and not planar.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Using a vertical structure, it is possible for the transistor to sustain both high blocking voltage and high current.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The voltage rating of the transistor is a function of the doping and thickness of the N-epitaxial layer (see cross section), while the current rating is a function of the channel width (the wider the channel, the higher the current).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] In a planar structure, the current and breakdown voltage ratings are both a function of the channel dimensions (respectively width and length of the channel), resulting in inefficient use of the "silicon estate".
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] With the vertical structure, the component area is roughly proportional to the current it can sustain, and the component thickness (actually the N-epitaxial layer thickness) is proportional to the breakdown voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Power MOSFETs with lateral structure are mainly used in high-end audio amplifiers and high-power PA systems.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Their advantage is a better behaviour in the saturated region (corresponding to the linear region of a bipolar transistor) than the vertical MOSFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Vertical MOSFETs are designed for switching applications.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] There are *LDMOS* (lateral double-diffused metal oxide semiconductor) and *VDMOS* (vertical double-diffused metal oxide semiconductor).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Most power MOSFETs are made using this technology.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Semiconductor sub-micrometer and nanometer electronic circuits are the primary concern for operating within the normal tolerance in harsh radiation environments like outer space.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] One of the design approaches for making a radiation-hardened-by-design (RHBD) device is enclosed-layout-transistor (ELT).
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Normally, the gate of the MOSFET surrounds the drain, which is placed in the center of the ELT.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The source of the MOSFET surrounds the gate.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Both of these transistors have very low leakage currents with respect to radiation.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] However, they are large in size and take up more space on silicon than a standard MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] In older STI (shallow trench isolation) designs, radiation strikes near the silicon oxide region cause the channel inversion at the corners of the standard MOSFET due to accumulation of radiation induced trapped charges.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] If the charges are large enough, the accumulated charges affect STI surface edges along the channel near the channel interface (gate) of the standard MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] This causes a device channel inversion to occur along the channel edges, creating an off-state leakage path.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Subsequently, the device turns on; this process severely degrades the reliability of circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] The ELT offers many advantages, including an improvement of reliability by reducing unwanted surface inversion at the gate edges which occurs in the standard MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Since the gate edges are enclosed in ELT, there is no gate oxide edge (STI at gate interface), and thus the transistor off-state leakage is reduced very much.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] Low-power microelectronic circuits including computers, communication devices, and monitoring systems in space shuttles and satellites are very different from what is used on earth.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] They are radiation (high-speed atomic particles like proton and neutron, solar flare magnetic energy dissipation in Earth's space, energetic cosmic rays like X-ray, gamma ray etc.) tolerant circuits.
[src:cmos-technology/mosfet-p02] These special electronics are designed by applying different techniques using RHBD MOSFETs to ensure safe space journeys and safe space-walks of astronauts.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A **multigate device**, **multi-gate MOSFET** or **multi-gate field-effect transistor** (**MuGFET**) refers to a metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) that has more than one gate on a single transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The multiple gates may be controlled by a single gate electrode, wherein the multiple gate surfaces act electrically as a single gate, or by independent gate electrodes.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A multigate device employing independent gate electrodes is sometimes called a **multiple-independent-gate field-effect transistor** (**MIGFET**).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The most widely used multi-gate devices are the FinFET (fin field-effect transistor) and the GAAFET (gate-all-around field-effect transistor), which are non-planar transistors, or **3D transistors**.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The primary roadblock to widespread implementation is manufacturability, as both planar and non-planar designs present significant challenges, especially with respect to lithography and patterning.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Other complementary strategies for device scaling include channel strain engineering, silicon-on-insulator-based technologies, and high-κ/metal gate materials.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Dual-gate MOSFETs are commonly used in very high frequency (VHF) mixers and in sensitive VHF front-end amplifiers.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] They are available from manufacturers such as Motorola, NXP Semiconductors, and Hitachi.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Dozens of multigate transistor variants may be found in the literature.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In general, these variants may be differentiated and classified in terms of architecture (planar vs. non-planar design) and the number of channels/gates (2, 3, or 4).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In planar double-gate transistors the drain–source channel is sandwiched between two independently fabricated gate/gate-oxide stacks.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The primary challenge in fabricating such structures is achieving satisfactory self-alignment between the upper and lower gates.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] FinFET (fin field-effect transistor) is a type of non-planar transistor, or "3D" transistor (not to be confused with 3D microchips).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The FinFET is a variation on traditional MOSFETs distinguished by the presence of a thin silicon "fin" inversion channel on top of the substrate, allowing the gate to make two points of contact: the left and right sides of the fin.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The thickness of the fin (measured in the direction from source to drain) determines the effective channel length of the device.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The wrap-around gate structure provides a better electrical control over the channel and thus helps in reducing the leakage current and overcoming other short-channel effects.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The first FinFET transistor type was called a *depleted lean-channel transistor* or "DELTA" transistor, which was first fabricated by Hitachi Central Research Laboratory's Digh Hisamoto, Toru Kaga, Yoshifumi Kawamoto and Eiji Takeda in 1989.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In the late 1990s, Digh Hisamoto began collaborating with an international team of researchers on further developing DELTA technology, including TSMC's Chenming Hu and a UC Berkeley research team including Tsu-Jae King Liu, Jeffrey Bokor, Xuejue Huang, Leland Chang, Nick Lindert, S.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Ahmed, Cyrus Tabery, Yang-Kyu Choi, Pushkar Ranade, Sriram Balasubramanian, A.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In 1998, the team developed the first N-channel FinFETs and successfully fabricated devices down to a 17 nm process.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The following year, they developed the first P-channel FinFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] They coined the term "FinFET" (fin field-effect transistor) in a December 2000 paper.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In current usage the term FinFET has a less precise definition.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Among microprocessor manufacturers, AMD, IBM, and Freescale describe their double-gate development efforts as FinFET development, whereas Intel avoids using the term when describing their closely related tri-gate architecture.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In the technical literature, FinFET is used somewhat generically to describe any fin-based, multigate transistor architecture regardless of number of gates.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] It is common for a single FinFET transistor to contain several fins, arranged side by side and all covered by the same gate, that act electrically as one, to increase drive strength and performance.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The gate may also cover the entirety of the fin(s).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A 25 nm transistor operating on just 0.7 volt was demonstrated in December 2002 by TSMC (Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The "Omega FinFET" design is named after the similarity between the Greek letter omega (Ω) and the shape in which the gate wraps around the source/drain structure.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] It has a gate delay of just 0.39 picosecond (ps) for the N-type transistor and 0.88 ps for the P-type.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In 2004, Samsung Electronics demonstrated a "Bulk FinFET" design, which made it possible to mass-produce FinFET devices.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In 2006, a team of Korean researchers from the Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (KAIST) and the National Nano Fab Center developed a 3 nm transistor, the world's smallest nanoelectronic device, based on FinFET technology.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In 2012, Intel started using FinFETs for its future commercial devices.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In September 2012, GlobalFoundries announced plans to offer a 14-nanometer process technology featuring FinFET three-dimensional transistors in 2014.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The next month, the rival company TSMC announced start early or "risk" production of 16 nm FinFETs in November 2013.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] AMD released GPUs using their Polaris chip architecture and made on 14 nm FinFET in June 2016.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The company has tried to produce a design to provide a "generational jump in power efficiency" while also offering stable frame rates for graphics, gaming, virtual reality, and multimedia applications.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In March 2017, Samsung and eSilicon announced the tapeout for production of a 14 nm FinFET ASIC in a 2.5D package.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A **tri-gate** transistor, also known as a triple-gate transistor, is a type of MOSFET with a gate on three of its sides.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A triple-gate transistor was first demonstrated in 1987, by a Toshiba research team including K.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] They realized that the fully depleted (FD) body of a narrow bulk Si-based transistor helped improve switching due to a reduced body-bias effect.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In 1992, a triple-gate MOSFET was demonstrated by IBM researcher Hon-Sum Wong.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Intel announced this technology in September 2002.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Intel announced "triple-gate transistors" which maximize "transistor switching performance and decreases power-wasting leakage".
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A year later, in September 2003, AMD announced that it was working on similar technology at the International Conference on Solid State Devices and Materials.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] No further announcements of this technology were made until Intel's announcement in May 2011, although it was stated at IDF 2011, that they demonstrated a working SRAM chip based on this technology at IDF 2009.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] On April 23, 2012, Intel released a new line of CPUs, termed Ivy Bridge, which feature tri-gate transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Intel has been working on its tri-gate architecture since 2002, but it took until 2011 to work out mass-production issues.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The new style of transistor was described on May 4, 2011, in San Francisco.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] It was announced that Intel's factories were expected to make upgrades over 2011 and 2012 to be able to manufacture the Ivy Bridge CPUs.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] It was announced that the new transistors would also be used in Intel's Atom chips for low-powered devices.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Tri-gate fabrication was used by Intel for the non-planar transistor architecture used in Ivy Bridge, Haswell and Skylake processors.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] These transistors employ a single gate stacked on top of two vertical gates (a single gate wrapped over three sides of the channel), allowing essentially three times the surface area for electrons to travel.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Intel reports that their tri-gate transistors reduce leakage and consume far less power than previous transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] This allows up to 37% higher speed or a power consumption at under 50% of the previous type of transistors used by Intel.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The term *tri-gate* is sometimes used generically to denote any multigate FET with three effective gates or channels.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] GAAFET, also known as a surrounding-gate transistor (SGT), is similar in concept to a FinFET except that the gate material surrounds the channel region on all sides.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Depending on design, gate-all-around FETs can have two or four effective gates.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Gate-all-around FETs have been successfully characterized both theoretically and experimentally.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] They have also been successfully etched onto nanowires of InGaAs, which have a higher electron mobility than silicon.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A gate-all-around (GAA) MOSFET was first demonstrated in 1988, by a Toshiba research team including Fujio Masuoka, Hiroshi Takato, and Kazumasa Sunouchi, who demonstrated a vertical nanowire GAAFET which they called a "surrounding gate transistor" (SGT).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Masuoka, best known as the inventor of flash memory, later left Toshiba and founded Unisantis Electronics in 2004 to research surrounding-gate technology along with Tohoku University.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] GAAFET transistors may make use of high-k/metal gate materials.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] GAAFETs with up to 7 nanosheets have been demonstrated which allow for improved performance and/or reduced device footprint.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The widths of the nanosheets in GAAFETs is controllable which more easily allows for the adjustment of device characteristics.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] As of 2020, Samsung and Intel have announced plans to mass produce GAAFET transistors (specifically MBCFET transistors) while TSMC has announced that they will continue to use FinFETs in their 3 nm node, despite TSMC developing GAAFET transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] A multi-bridge channel FET (MBCFET) is similar to a GAAFET except for the use of nanosheets instead of nanowires.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] MBCFET is a word mark (trademark) registered in the U.S. to Samsung Electronics.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Samsung plans on mass producing MBCFET transistors at the 3 nm node for its foundry customers.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Intel is also developing RibbonFET, a variation of MBCFET "nanoribbon" transistors.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Unlike FinFETs, both the width and the number of the sheets can be varied to adjust drive strength or the amount of current the transistor can drive at a given voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The sheets often vary from 8 to 50 nanometers in width.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The width of the nanosheets is known as Weff, or effective width.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Planar transistors have been the core of integrated circuits for several decades, during which the size of the individual transistors has steadily decreased.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] As the size decreases, planar transistors increasingly suffer from the undesirable short-channel effect, especially "off-state" leakage current, which increases the idle power required by the device.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] In a multigate device, the channel is surrounded by several gates on multiple surfaces.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Thus it provides better electrical control over the channel, allowing more effective suppression of "off-state" leakage current.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Multiple gates also allow enhanced current in the "on" state, also known as drive current.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Multigate transistors also provide a better analog performance due to a higher intrinsic gain and lower channel length modulation.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] These advantages translate to lower power consumption and enhanced device performance.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Nonplanar devices are also more compact than conventional planar transistors, enabling higher transistor density which translates to smaller overall microelectronics.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] BSIMCMG106.0.0, officially released on March 1, 2012 by UC Berkeley BSIM Group, is the first standard model for FinFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Physical surface-potential-based formulations are derived for both intrinsic and extrinsic models with finite body doping.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The surface potentials at the source and drain ends are solved analytically with poly-depletion and quantum mechanical effects.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The effect of finite body doping is captured through a perturbation approach.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The analytic surface potential solution agrees closely with the 2-D device simulation results.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] If the channel doping concentration is low enough to be neglected, computational efficiency can be further improved by a setting a specific flag (COREMOD = 1).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] All of the important multi-gate (MG) transistor behavior is captured by this model.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Volume inversion is included in the solution of Poisson's equation, hence the subsequent I–V formulation automatically captures the volume-inversion effect.
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] Analysis of electrostatic potential in the body of MG MOSFETs provided a model equation for short-channel effects (SCE).
[src:cmos-technology/multigate-device] The extra electrostatic control from the end gates (top/bottom gates) (triple or quadruple-gate) is also captured in the short-channel model.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] In semiconductor manufacturing, **silicon on insulator** (**SOI**) technology is fabrication of silicon semiconductor devices in a layered silicon–insulator–silicon substrate, to reduce parasitic capacitance within the device, thereby improving performance.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] SOI-based devices differ from conventional silicon-built devices in that the silicon junction is above an electrical insulator, typically silicon dioxide or sapphire (these types of devices are called silicon on sapphire, or SOS).
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The choice of insulator depends largely on intended application, with sapphire being used for high-performance radio frequency (RF) and radiation-sensitive applications, and silicon dioxide for diminished short-channel effects in other microelectronics devices.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The insulating layer and topmost silicon layer also vary widely with application.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] SOI technology is one of several manufacturing strategies to allow the continued miniaturization of microelectronic devices, colloquially referred to as "extending Moore's law" (or "more moore", abbreviated "MM").
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] From a manufacturing perspective, SOI substrates are compatible with most conventional fabrication processes.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] In general, an SOI-based process may be implemented without special equipment or significant retooling of an existing factory.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Among challenges unique to SOI are novel metrology requirements to account for the buried oxide layer and concerns about differential stress in the topmost silicon layer.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The threshold voltage of the transistor depends on the history of operation and applied voltage to it, thus making modeling harder.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The primary barrier to SOI implementation is the drastic increase in substrate cost, which contributes an estimated 10–15% increase to total manufacturing costs.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] An SOI MOSFET is a metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) device in which a semiconductor layer such as silicon or germanium is formed on an insulator layer which may be a buried oxide (BOX) layer formed in a semiconductor substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] SOI MOSFET devices are adapted for use by the computer industry.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The buried oxide layer can be used in SRAM designs.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] There are two types of SOI devices: PDSOI (partially depleted SOI) and FDSOI (fully depleted SOI) MOSFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] For a PDSOI P-MOSFET the sandwiched n-type film between the gate oxide (GOX) and buried oxide (BOX) is large, so the depletion region can't cover the whole n region.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] So to some extent PDSOI behaves like bulk MOSFET.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Obviously there are some advantages over the bulk MOSFETs.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The film is very thin in FDSOI devices so that the depletion region covers the whole channel region.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] In FDSOI the front gate (GOX) supports fewer depletion charges than the bulk so an increase in inversion charges occurs resulting in higher switching speeds.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The limitation of the depletion charge by the BOX induces a suppression of the depletion capacitance and therefore a substantial reduction of the subthreshold swing allowing FD SOI MOSFETs to work at lower gate bias resulting in lower power operation.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The subthreshold swing can reach the minimum theoretical value for MOSFET at 300K, which is 60mV/decade.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] This ideal value was first demonstrated using numerical simulation.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Other drawbacks in bulk MOSFETs, like threshold voltage roll off, etc. are reduced in FDSOI since the source and drain electric fields can't interfere due to the BOX.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The main problem in PDSOI is the "floating body effect (FBE)" since the film is not connected to any of the supplies.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] IBM began to use SOI in the high-end RS64-IV "Istar" PowerPC-AS microprocessor in 2000.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Other examples of microprocessors built on SOI technology include AMD's 130 nm, 90 nm, 65 nm, 45 nm and 32 nm single, dual, quad, six and eight core processors since 2001.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Freescale adopted SOI in their PowerPC 7455 CPU in late 2001, currently Freescale is shipping SOI products in 180 nm, 130 nm, 90 nm and 45 nm lines.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The 90 nm PowerPC- and Power ISA-based processors used in the Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, and Wii use SOI technology as well.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Competitive offerings from Intel however continue to use conventional bulk CMOS technology for each process node, instead focusing on other venues such as HKMG and tri-gate transistors to improve transistor performance.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] In January 2005, Intel researchers reported on an experimental single-chip silicon rib waveguide Raman laser built using SOI.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] As for the traditional foundries, in July 2006 TSMC claimed no customer wanted SOI, but Chartered Semiconductor devoted a whole fab to SOI.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] In 1990, Peregrine Semiconductor began development of an SOI process technology utilizing a standard 0.5 μm CMOS node and an enhanced sapphire substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Its patented silicon on sapphire (SOS) process is widely used in high-performance RF applications.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The intrinsic benefits of the insulating sapphire substrate allow for high isolation, high linearity and electro-static discharge (ESD) tolerance.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Multiple other companies have also applied SOI technology to successful RF applications in smartphones and cellular radios.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The superior electrical isolation of SOI substrates makes the technology pivotal for a wide range of modern RF components.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] This enables the development of highly integrated, efficient, and linear circuits that are critical for advanced communication systems.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] Key applications leveraging these advantages include RF waveguides for 5G networks and satellite communications, high-linearity RF amplifiers and transceivers for automotive and virtual reality applications, and compact, tunable RF filters for next-generation wireless devices.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The technology's ability to integrate multiple RF components onto a single chip supports the ongoing trend towards more compact and multifunctional wireless communication systems.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] SOI wafers are widely used in silicon photonics.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The crystalline silicon layer on insulator can be used to fabricate optical waveguides and other optical devices, either passive or active (e.g. through suitable implantations).
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The buried insulator enables propagation of infrared light in the silicon layer on the basis of total internal reflection.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] The major disadvantage of SOI technology when compared to conventional semiconductor industry is increased cost of manufacturing.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] As of 2012 only IBM and AMD used SOI as basis for high-performance processors and the other manufacturers (Intel, TSMC, Global Foundries etc.) used conventional silicon wafers to build their CMOS chips.
[src:cmos-technology/silicon-on-insulator] As of 2020 the market utilizing the SOI process was projected to grow up by ~15% for the next 5 years according to Market Research Future group.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The **threshold voltage**, commonly abbreviated as Vth or VGS(th), of a field-effect transistor (FET) is the minimum gate-to-source voltage (VGS) that is needed to create a conducting path between the source and drain terminals.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] It is an important scaling factor to maintain power efficiency.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] When referring to a junction field-effect transistor (JFET), the threshold voltage is often called **pinch-off voltage** instead.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] This is somewhat confusing since *pinch off* applied to insulated-gate field-effect transistor (IGFET) refers to the channel pinching that leads to current saturation behavior under high source–drain bias, even though the current is never off.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Unlike *pinch off*, the term *threshold voltage* is unambiguous and refers to the same concept in any field-effect transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In n-channel *enhancement-mode* devices, a conductive channel does not exist naturally within the transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] With no VGS, dopant ions added to the body of the FET form a region with no mobile carriers called a depletion region.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] A positive VGS attracts free-floating electrons within the body towards the gate.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] But enough electrons must be attracted near the gate to counter the dopant ions and form a conductive channel.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The conductive channel connects from source to drain at the FET's *threshold voltage*.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Even more electrons attract towards the gate at higher VGS, which widens the channel.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The reverse is true for the p-channel "enhancement-mode" MOS transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] When VGS = 0 the device is “OFF” and the channel is open / non-conducting.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The application of a negative gate voltage to the p-type "enhancement-mode" MOSFET enhances the channels conductivity turning it “ON”.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In contrast, n-channel *depletion-mode* devices have a conductive channel naturally existing within the transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Accordingly, the term *threshold voltage* does not readily apply to *turning* such devices on, but is used instead to denote the voltage level at which the channel is wide enough to allow electrons to flow easily.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] For the n-channel depletion MOS transistor, a sufficient negative VGS will deplete (hence its name) the conductive channel of its free electrons switching the transistor “OFF”.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Likewise for a p-channel "depletion-mode" MOS transistor a sufficient positive gate-source voltage will deplete the channel of its free holes, turning it “OFF”.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In wide planar transistors the threshold voltage is essentially independent of the drain–source voltage (VDS) and is therefore a well defined characteristic, however it is less clear in modern nanometer-sized MOSFETs due to drain-induced barrier lowering.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In the figures, the source (left side) and drain (right side) are labeled *n+* to indicate heavily doped (blue) n-regions.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The depletion layer dopant is labeled *NA−* to indicate that the ions in the (pink) depletion layer are negatively charged and there are very few holes.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In the (red) bulk the number of holes *p = NA* making the bulk charge neutral.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] If the gate voltage is below the threshold voltage (left figure), the "enhancement-mode" transistor is turned off and ideally there is no current from the drain to the source of the transistor.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In fact, there is a current even for gate biases below the threshold (subthreshold leakage) current, although it is small and varies exponentially with gate bias.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Therefore, datasheets will specify threshold voltage according to a specified measurable amount of current (commonly 250 μA or 1 mA).
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] If the gate voltage is above the threshold voltage (right figure), the "enhancement-mode" transistor is turned on, due to there being many electrons in the channel at the oxide-silicon interface, creating a low-resistance channel where charge can flow from drain to source.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] For voltages significantly above the threshold, this situation is called strong inversion.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The channel is tapered when *VD* > 0 because the voltage drop due to the current in the resistive channel reduces the oxide field supporting the channel as the drain is approached.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] The *body effect* is the change in the threshold voltage by an amount approximately equal to the change in the source-bulk voltage, $V_{SB}$ , because the body influences the threshold voltage (when it is not tied to the source).
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] It can be thought of as a second gate, and is sometimes referred to as the *back gate*, and accordingly the body effect is sometimes called the *back-gate effect*.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In a given technology node, such as the 90-nm CMOS process, the threshold voltage depends on the choice of oxide and on **oxide thickness**.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Using the body formulas above, $V_{TN}$ is directly proportional to $\gamma$ , and $t_{OX}$ , which is the parameter for oxide thickness.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Thus, the thinner the oxide thickness, the lower the threshold voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Although this may seem to be an improvement, it is not without cost; because the thinner the oxide thickness, the higher the subthreshold leakage current through the device will be.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Consequently, the design specification for 90-nm gate-oxide thickness was set at 1 nm to control the leakage current.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] This kind of tunneling, called Fowler-Nordheim Tunneling.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] $E_{ox}$ is the electric field across the gate oxide.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Before scaling the design features down to 90 nm, a dual-oxide approach for creating the oxide thickness was a common solution to this issue.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] With a 90 nm process technology, a triple-oxide approach has been adopted in some cases.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] One standard thin oxide is used for most transistors, another for I/O driver cells, and a third for memory-and-pass transistor cells.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] These differences are based purely on the characteristics of oxide thickness on threshold voltage of CMOS technologies.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] As with the case of oxide thickness affecting threshold voltage, temperature has an effect on the threshold voltage of a CMOS device.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] $n_{i}$ is the intrinsic doping parameter for the substrate.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] We see that the surface potential has a direct relationship with the temperature.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Looking above, that the threshold voltage does not have a direct relationship but is not independent of the effects.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] This variation is typically between −4 mV/K and −2 mV/K depending on doping level.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] For a change of 30 °C this results in significant variation from the 500 mV design parameter commonly used for the 90-nm technology node.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Random dopant fluctuation (RDF) is a form of process variation resulting from variation in the implanted impurity concentration.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In MOSFET transistors, RDF in the channel region can alter the transistor's properties, especially threshold voltage.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] In newer process technologies RDF has a larger effect because the total number of dopants is fewer.
[src:cmos-technology/threshold-voltage] Research works are being carried out in order to suppress the dopant fluctuation which leads to the variation of threshold voltage between devices undergoing same manufacturing process.
